  "prompt": "What are the best albums by Seal?",
  "response": "Seal has had a very strong career, but here are some of his best albums, considering both critical acclaim and commercial success:\n\n*   **Seal (1991):** Often referred to as \"Seal I\", this is arguably his masterpiece. It's a groundbreaking debut that introduced the world to his soulful voice, unique songwriting, and experimental blend of genres. Notable tracks include \"Crazy,\" \"Killer,\" and \"Future Love Paradise.\" This album is essential for understanding Seal's artistic vision.\n\n*   **Seal (1994):** Known as \"Seal II\", this album solidified his status as a major artist. It's more polished and commercially oriented than his debut but still retains his signature sound. It features the massive hit \"Kiss from a Rose,\" which propelled the album to multi-platinum status.\n\n*   **Human Being (1998):** This album is somewhat of an underrated gem. It's a darker, more introspective work that explores themes of identity and social commentary. While it didn't achieve the commercial success of his first two albums, it showcases Seal's willingness to experiment and push his artistic boundaries. Tracks like \"Human Beings\" and \"Latest Craze\" are standouts.\n\n*   **Soul (2008):** A covers album that paid homage to classic soul songs, it proved to be one of Seal's biggest commercial successes in later years. His versions of \"A Change is Gonna Come\" and \"I'm Still in Love with You\" are particularly well-received.\n\nHere's a little more nuance:\n\n*   **For the casual listener:** \"Seal\" (1994) is the most accessible due to \"Kiss from a Rose.\" \"Soul\" is also a good choice if you're into classic soul music.\n*   **For the Seal enthusiast:** \"Seal\" (1991) is essential. \"Human Being\" is worth exploring if you want to delve deeper into his artistry.\n\nUltimately, the \"best\" album is subjective, and depends on your personal taste. I would recommend listening to tracks from each album to see which one resonates most with you.",
